WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:05.505
Asthma is a chronic inflammatory airway
disease that causes variable and often reversible airflow

2
00:00:05.505 --> 00:00:06.065
obstruction.

3
00:00:06.965 --> 00:00:09.305
Patients experience wheezing, coughing,
chest tightness,

4
00:00:09.385 --> 00:00:10.324
and shortness of breath.

5
00:00:10.404 --> 00:00:13.404
But for respiratory therapists, the key is
not just hearing

6
00:00:13.404 --> 00:00:16.704
wheezing, it's determining how well the
patient is actually moving

7
00:00:16.704 --> 00:00:19.405
air and whether they are at risk of
respiratory failure.

8
00:00:19.565 --> 00:00:23.504
The underlying problem involves airway
inflammation, bronchospasm,

9
00:00:23.665 --> 00:00:24.444
and mucus production.

10
00:00:24.684 --> 00:00:27.844
When a trigger is introduced, the airway
becomes swollen and

11
00:00:27.844 --> 00:00:28.645
hyper-responsive.

12
00:00:29.014 --> 00:00:31.665
Smooth muscle constricts, mucus increases,
and

13
00:00:31.665 --> 00:00:32.424
the airway narrows.

14
00:00:33.084 --> 00:00:35.525
This makes exhalation difficult, leading
to air trapping,

15
00:00:35.884 --> 00:00:37.904
increased work of breathing, and possible
fatigue.

16
00:00:38.455 --> 00:00:41.965
Early in an exacerbation, patients often
hypermalate and have a

17
00:00:41.965 --> 00:00:42.944
low PaCO2.

18
00:00:43.185 --> 00:00:45.884
But as they tire, PaCO2 may rise,

19
00:00:45.965 --> 00:00:48.044
which is a dangerous sign of worsening
ventilation.

20
00:00:48.924 --> 00:00:51.584
Common triggers include allergens,
exercise, cold

21
00:00:51.584 --> 00:00:53.525
air, respiratory infections, smoke,

22
00:00:53.564 --> 00:00:54.345
and strong odors.

23
00:00:54.505 --> 00:00:57.444
And identifying these is important for
long-term control.

24
00:00:57.444 --> 00:01:00.145
Clinically, patients may present with
wheezing,

25
00:01:00.625 --> 00:01:02.544
dyspnea, cough, accessory muscle use,

26
00:01:02.604 --> 00:01:03.544
and difficulty speaking.

27
00:01:03.665 --> 00:01:06.584
But a key red flag is a silent chest,
which

28
00:01:06.584 --> 00:01:09.184
can indicate severe obstruction and
minimal airflow.

29
00:01:10.044 --> 00:01:14.425
Diagnostics include spirometry, showing a
decreased FEV1 over FVC ratio

30
00:01:14.425 --> 00:01:18.385
that improves with bronchodilator therapy,
confirming reversible obstruction.

31
00:01:19.205 --> 00:01:22.004
Peak flow helps assess severity, with 80
to 100% of

32
00:01:22.004 --> 00:01:25.404
personal best considered green, 50 to 79%
yellow,

33
00:01:25.565 --> 00:01:28.665
and below 50% red zone, indicating severe
risk.

34
00:01:29.245 --> 00:01:33.264
ABGs are also important, as a rising PaCO2
during distress

35
00:01:33.264 --> 00:01:35.324
suggests impending ventilatory failure.

36
00:01:36.324 --> 00:01:39.665
Treatment focuses on relieving
bronchospasm and controlling inflammation.

37
00:01:40.565 --> 00:01:44.864
Short-acting beta agonists like albuterol
provide rapid bronchodilation, while

38
00:01:44.864 --> 00:01:47.864
inhaled corticosteroids are the foundation
of long-term control.

39
00:01:48.285 --> 00:01:51.864
In moderate to severe exacerbations,
ipratropium may be added,

40
00:01:52.224 --> 00:01:54.684
and systemic steroids are used to reduce
inflammation.

41
00:01:55.464 --> 00:01:58.745
In severe cases known as status
asthmaticus, the patient does

42
00:01:58.745 --> 00:02:02.364
not respond to standard treatment and may
require escalation, including

43
00:02:02.364 --> 00:02:03.885
possible mechanical ventilation.

44
00:02:04.345 --> 00:02:07.345
In these situations, the goal is to
prevent air trapping

45
00:02:07.345 --> 00:02:10.725
by allowing longer expiratory time and
avoiding breath stacking.

46
00:02:11.085 --> 00:02:14.425
The respiratory therapist plays a critical
role in assessing ventilation,

47
00:02:15.184 --> 00:02:17.705
oxygenation, breath sounds, peak flow,

48
00:02:17.744 --> 00:02:20.945
and response to therapy, as well as
educating patients on

49
00:02:20.945 --> 00:02:22.565
inhaler use and trigger avoidance.

50
00:02:22.824 --> 00:02:26.505
The most important takeaway is that asthma
is a dynamic airflow problem.

51
00:02:27.065 --> 00:02:28.824
Never judge severity by wheezing alone.

52
00:02:29.244 --> 00:02:31.345
A patient who becomes quieter, more
fatigued,

53
00:02:31.425 --> 00:02:35.024
or shows a rising PaCO2 is not improving,
they are

54
00:02:35.024 --> 00:02:38.184
getting worse, and recognizing that early
can save a life.

